Looking at the code fragments, I can see that Hexi uses a `file_buffer` class and `binary_stream` for reading/writing operations. Here's the implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/file_buffer.h>
#include <cstdint>
#include <filesystem>

uint32_t read_uint32_from_file(const std::filesystem::path& file_path) {
    hexi::file_buffer buffer(file_path);
    hexi::binary_stream stream(buffer);
    uint32_t value;
    stream >> value;
    return value;
}

void write_uint32_to_file(const std::filesystem::path& file_path, uint32_t value) {
    hexi::file_buffer buffer(file_path);
    hexi::binary_stream stream(buffer);
    stream << value;
}
```

However, based on the code fragments showing that `file_buffer` opens files in "a+b" mode (append and read), and considering that we might want to overwrite the file content when writing, here's a more robust version:

```cpp
#include <hexi/file_buffer.h>
#include <cstdint>
#include <filesystem>

uint32_t read_uint32_from_file(const std::filesystem::path& file_path) {
    // Create file_buffer for reading
    hexi::file_buffer buffer(file_path);

    // Create binary stream with the buffer
    hexi::binary_stream stream(buffer);

    // Read the uint32_t value
    uint32_t value;
    stream >> value;

    return value;
}

void write_uint32_to_file(const std::filesystem::path& file_path, uint32_t value) {
    // Create file_buffer for writing (opens in "a+b" mode)
    hexi::file_buffer buffer(file_path);

    // Create binary stream with the buffer
    hexi::binary_stream stream(buffer);

    // Write the uint32_t value
    stream << value;
}
```

The key points:
1. `hexi::file_buffer` is used to create a file buffer from the path
2. `hexi::binary_stream` is created from the file buffer for stream operations
3. The stream operators `>>` and `<<` are used to read/write the uint32_t values
4. The file_buffer constructor handles opening the file in the appropriate mode

This implementation follows the pattern shown in the code fragments where `binary_stream` is used with various buffer types for serialization/deserialization operations.

