Looking at the Hexi library code fragments, I can see that `hexi::file_buffer` is a read-only file buffer that doesn't support seeking. To implement the preview function without advancing the read pointer, we need to create a temporary file buffer, read the header data, and then discard the buffer without affecting the original file position.

Here's the complete implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/file_buffer.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>
#include <filesystem>

std::vector<uint8_t> preview_file_header(const std::filesystem::path& file_path, size_t header_size) {
    // Create a temporary file buffer to read the header
    hexi::file_buffer file(file_path.string().c_str());

    // Create a buffer to store the header data
    std::vector<uint8_t> header_data;
    header_data.resize(header_size);

    // Read the header data using the file buffer's read function
    // The file_buffer will be destroyed after this function, so the read pointer
    // of the original file (if opened elsewhere) won't be affected
    auto bytes_read = file.read(reinterpret_cast<char*>(header_data.data()), header_size);

    // Resize the vector to the actual number of bytes read
    if (bytes_read != hexi::file_buffer::npos) {
        header_data.resize(bytes_read);
    } else {
        // If read failed, return empty vector
        header_data.clear();
    }

    return header_data;
}
```

Alternative implementation using binary_stream for more robust error handling:

```cpp
#include <hexi/file_buffer.h>
#include <hexi/binary_stream.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>
#include <filesystem>

std::vector<uint8_t> preview_file_header(const std::filesystem::path& file_path, size_t header_size) {
    // Create a temporary file buffer
    hexi::file_buffer file(file_path.string().c_str());

    // Create binary stream with the file buffer
    hexi::binary_stream stream(file, hexi::no_throw);

    std::vector<uint8_t> header_data;
    header_data.resize(header_size);

    // Try to read the header data
    if (stream.read(header_data.data(), header_size)) {
        // Successfully read the header
        return header_data;
    } else {
        // Read failed, return empty vector or partial data
        header_data.clear();
        return header_data;
    }
}
```

The key points of this implementation:

1. **Temporary file buffer**: We create a new `hexi::file_buffer` instance that will be destroyed when the function exits, ensuring the original file's read pointer (if any) is not affected.

2. **No seeking required**: Since `hexi::file_buffer` doesn't support seeking (`using seeking = unsupported;`), we rely on creating a fresh buffer instance.

3. **Error handling**: The implementation handles cases where the file might be smaller than the requested header size or when the file cannot be opened.

4. **Clean resource management**: The file buffer is automatically closed when the function returns, ensuring no resource leaks.

The function returns the header data as a vector of bytes, which can be inspected before deciding whether to read the full file content.

