Looking at the provided code fragments, I can see that `hexi::static_buffer` has methods for writing and reading data. Here's the complete implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/static_buffer.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>

template<size_t buffer_size = 1024>
void write_data_to_buffer(hexi::static_buffer<std::byte, buffer_size>& buffer, const std::vector<uint8_t>& data) {
    // Write the data to the buffer
    buffer.write(reinterpret_cast<const std::byte*>(data.data()), data.size());
}

template<size_t buffer_size = 1024>
std::vector<uint8_t> read_data_from_buffer(hexi::static_buffer<std::byte, buffer_size>& buffer, size_t bytes_to_read) {
    // Create a vector to hold the read data
    std::vector<uint8_t> result(bytes_to_read);

    // Read the data from the buffer
    buffer.read(reinterpret_cast<std::byte*>(result.data()), bytes_to_read);

    return result;
}
```

This implementation:

1. **`write_data_to_buffer`**: Uses the buffer's `write` method to write the entire contents of the input vector to the buffer. The `uint8_t` data is cast to `std::byte` using `reinterpret_cast`.

2. **`read_data_from_buffer`**: Creates a vector of the requested size, then uses the buffer's `read` method to read the specified number of bytes into the vector. The result vector's data is cast to `std::byte` for the read operation.

The implementation assumes that the buffer has sufficient space for the write operation and sufficient data for the read operation. If you need error handling for buffer overflow/underflow, you would need to check the buffer's size before performing the operations.

