Based on the provided code fragments and the Hexi library's buffer_adaptor interface, here's the complete implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_adaptor.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>

void write_data_to_buffer(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer, uint32_t value, const void* data, std::size_t length) {
    // Write the integer value (4 bytes)
    buffer.write(&value, sizeof(value));

    // Write the byte array
    buffer.write(data, length);
}

void read_data_from_buffer(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer, uint32_t& value, void* data, std::size_t length) {
    // Read the integer value (4 bytes)
    buffer.read(&value, sizeof(value));

    // Read the byte array
    buffer.read(data, length);
}

struct BufferInfo {
    std::size_t size;
    std::size_t free_space;
};

BufferInfo get_buffer_info(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer) {
    BufferInfo info;
    info.size = buffer.size();

    // For free space, we need to calculate based on the underlying vector's capacity
    // Since buffer_adaptor wraps a vector, we can't directly get capacity from the adaptor
    // This is a limitation - we'd need access to the original vector to get capacity
    info.free_space = 0; // Cannot determine free space without the original container

    return info;
}
```

However, I notice there's an issue with the `get_buffer_info` function - the `buffer_adaptor` interface doesn't seem to provide a way to get the capacity of the underlying container. Looking at the code fragments, the `buffer_adaptor` has a `size()` method but no `capacity()` method.

If you need to get the actual free space, you might need to modify the function signature to also accept the original vector:

```cpp
BufferInfo get_buffer_info(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer, const std::vector<std::byte>& underlying_vector) {
    BufferInfo info;
    info.size = buffer.size();
    info.free_space = underlying_vector.capacity() - buffer.size();
    return info;
}
```

Alternatively, if the `buffer_adaptor` provides access to the underlying container, you could use that. But based on the provided code fragments, it doesn't appear to expose the container directly.

The first version with the limitation noted in the comment is the most accurate implementation given the available interface information.

