Looking at the Hexi library's buffer adaptor interface, I can see that `buffer_adaptor` inherits from `buffer_read` which provides methods for accessing the buffer data. Here's the complete implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_adaptor.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_read.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>

std::size_t find_byte_in_buffer(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer, std::byte value) {
    // Get a pointer to the current read position and the available size
    const std::byte* data = buffer.read_ptr();
    std::size_t size = buffer.size();

    // Search for the byte value in the buffer
    for (std::size_t i = 0; i < size; ++i) {
        if (data[i] == value) {
            return i; // Return position if found
        }
    }

    return hexi::pmc::buffer_read::npos; // Return npos if not found
}

std::size_t find_delimiter_position(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer, std::byte delimiter) {
    // This is essentially the same as find_byte_in_buffer but with a more descriptive name
    return find_byte_in_buffer(buffer, delimiter);
}

bool check_buffer_contains(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer, std::byte value) {
    // Use find_byte_in_buffer and check if the result is not npos
    return find_byte_in_buffer(buffer, value) != hexi::pmc::buffer_read::npos;
}
```

The implementation uses the `read_ptr()` method to get a pointer to the current readable data in the buffer and `size()` to get the number of available bytes. It then performs a linear search through the buffer to find the target byte value.

Key points:
- `read_ptr()` gives access to the current readable portion of the buffer
- `size()` returns the number of bytes available for reading
- `hexi::pmc::buffer_read::npos` is used as the "not found" indicator
- `find_delimiter_position` is essentially an alias for `find_byte_in_buffer` with a more semantic name
- `check_buffer_contains` simply checks if the find operation returns a valid position

